defaultOther countries have introduced minimum pricing policies for alcohol and their experience provides empirical evidence of 
defaultthe impact and benefits of MUP.  
defaultThe experience of the provinces of Canada is most similar to the form of MUP under consideration in the UK and we would be happy to provide further briefing to the Committee if this would be helpful. 
default&#xa0;defaultPHE’s review of the hdefaultealth impacts of shale gas extractiondefault&#xa0;defaultIn relation to our discussion on the health impact of shale gas extraction there were three points the Committee wanted me to comment further on.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe first was the request to see the evidence that we co
defaultnsidered as part of our review.  
defaultThe full list of references is set out at Annex B. 
default 
defaultWe used the best available international information about the process of shale gas extraction to estimate the likely emissions from shale gas extraction, as operated in t
defaulthe context of the UK regulatory environment, and evaluate any health risks associated with those emissions.  Although shale gas extraction is itself a relatively new process, the substances involved in any emissions, and many of the industrial processes ar
defaulte not new and their
default risks are well characterised.  
defaultFor that reason we were able to draw firm conclusions about risk in relation to chemical and radiological emissions, albeit with some caveats.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe Committee expressed concerns over the nature of some of t
defaulthe chemicals that may be used in shale gas extraction.  The UK will adopt a risk-based approach to the use of chemicals, and will assess the requirements for each development proposal on a site-by-site basis.  Any chemicals proposed for use in shale gas ex
defaulttraction fluid need not only to be publically disclosed, but will also be risk assessed prior to use by the Environment Agency, with subsequent peer review by the joint agencies groundwater directive advisory group (which includes PHE).
default&#xa0;
defaultI would also like 
defaultto provide further information on the origin and governance of the report. 
default 
defaultOur predecessor, the Health Protection Agency (HPA), initiated the review in early 2012 in response to requests for advice on the potential health impacts of shale gas extraction f
defaultrom a wide range of stakeholders including Local Authorities, 
defaultDirectors of Public Health, NHS bodies and members of the public.  The HPA proposal for a review, and its proposed scope, was endorsed by a range of UK public health bodie
defaults and environmental reg
defaultulators.  
defaultOn 
default 
default1 April 2013 PHE took on the functions of the HPA.  PHE agreed the review should continue, and that PHE would publish the results.  Any other decision would have called into question the ability of our scientists to contribute to publi
defaultc debate on the basis of the evidence.
default&#xa0;
defaultWe consider the findings of our review to be valid and robust within the scope of the draft report, and note that they are consistent with the conclusions reached in a recent Royal Society report into hydraulic fract
defaulturing (see link 
defaulthttp://royalsociety.org/policy/projects/shal
defaulte
default-gas-extracti
defaulto
defaultn/report
default).
